Notice

The Load Balancer automatically distributes requests.

Request 1 → Pod 1

Request 2 → Pod 2

Request 3 → Pod 1

Request 4 → Pod 2
Where is the Load Balancer created?

This is important.

Kubernetes doesn't create the Load Balancer itself.

AWS does.

You

↓

kubectl apply

↓

Kubernetes

↓

AWS API

↓

Creates

Application Load Balancer / Network Load Balancer

Exactly like Terraform creating an EC2.

Kubernetes talks to AWS APIs.

How do you find the Load Balancer?

Run

kubectl get svc

Output:

NAME            TYPE           EXTERNAL-IP
emailservice    LoadBalancer   a12bc34.elb.amazonaws.com

Sometimes initially you'll see

EXTERNAL-IP

<pending>

After a minute or two it changes to

a12bc34.elb.amazonaws.com

Then you access

http://a12bc34.elb.amazonaws.com:8080

(or just http://a12bc34.elb.amazonaws.com if the Load Balancer listens on port 80 and forwards to your Service).

What about NodePort?

Even if you don't specify it,

AWS still creates one internally.

Think of it like this:

Internet
      │
      ▼
AWS Load Balancer
      │
      ▼
NodePort
      │
      ▼
Pods

So a LoadBalancer Service is essentially:

NodePort + Cloud Load Balancer

The NodePort is usually hidden from you, but it's still there unless your cloud integration uses a different implementation.

Why use LoadBalancer?

Imagine you have three worker nodes.

Node 1

Node 2

Node 3

If Node 2 dies,

the AWS Load Balancer automatically sends traffic only to the healthy nodes.

Internet
      │
      ▼
Load Balancer
      │
 ┌────┴────┐
 ▼         ▼
Node 1   Node 3

You don't have to remember node IPs or ports.
